<title>GERMANY: German govt optimistic on EMU goals in 1997.</title>
<headline>German govt optimistic on EMU goals in 1997.</headline>
<dateline>BONN 1997-03-05</dateline>
<text>
<p>The German government is optimistic it will meet the Maastricht criteria for European monetary union (EMU) this year, despite current record unemployment, government spokesman Peter Hausmann said on Wednesday.</p>
<p>Finance Minister Theo Waigel has projected Germany's deficit in 1997 will be 2.9 percent of gross domestic product, below the 3.0 percent Maastricht guideline, but he concedes that controlling deficits is the biggest challenge facing EMU.</p>
<p>The decision on which countries will participate in EMU at the January 1999 start will be made in about one year, based on 1997 economic data.</p>
</text>
